    %p Higher numbers are formed on the basis of the nouns <i>mite</i> “hundred”, <i>mil</i> “thousand”, <i>milion</i> “million”, etc. Note that unlike the forms discussed up to this point, these are true nouns, not quantifiers; they therefore do not display gender agreement and can themselves be quantified, having singular and plural forms rather than masculine and feminine ones. Multiples of these forms are therefore expressed through quantification: <i>pare n mits</i> “two hundred” (lit. “two hundreds”). Intermediate numbers appear as uncoordinated adjuncts: <i>catr yn mils, pare n mits, treit’ e seft(e)</i> “four-thousand two-hundred and thirty-seven”. Note that since <i>mite</i> is femininee and <i>mil</i> is masculine, their respective quantifiers show differing gender agreement.
